Actually, in my initial version (when the use of `int64_t` was not implemented):
```
 auto nWorkers = DefineNumbWorkers<xpu>(shape, axis);
 bool use_uin16 = false;
  while (nWorkers > 1) {
    const size_t num_items = nWorkers * shape.Size() / shape[axis];
      pIdxMemory = AllocateDTypeMemory<xpu, uint32_t>(ctx, num_items);
      if (pIdxMemory)
        break;

    // Check if indexes can be stored in uint16 format
    if (shape[axis] <= UINT16_MAX) {
      pIdxMemory = AllocateDTypeMemory<xpu, uint16_t>(ctx, num_items);
      if (pIdxMemory) {
        use_uin16 = true;
        break;
      }
    }

    // Decreasing the number of workers - less memory will be needed
    nWorkers >>= 1;
  }
```
I was getting "optimal" value of `nWorkers` first, and I tried to allocate memory for indexes in "unsigned" formats.  Perhaps, it is not always true (and, please, correct me, if I am wrong), but I noticed that with `uint32_t` pointers the program runs 5-10% faster than with `uint16_t`. Because of that, I was trying to allocate memory in that order. 
When 
- (a) for some value of `nWorkers` the program fails to allocate `uint32_t *` memory AND
- (b) `shape[axis] <= UINT16_MAX`, therefore it is still possible to use `uint16_t *` memory, 

I was trying to allocate and use `uint16_t *` memory for the same value of `nWorkers`. But, if
- (a) is not possible to use "shorter" memory (`shape[axis] > UINT16_MAX)` OR 
- (b) the attempt to allocate it failed, 

I reduced nWorkers >> = 1 and started a new round of memory allocation with smaller `nWorkers`. (Yes, now `nWorkers` is not optimal, but it's better to as much as possible workers!).

After I started to use `index_t`, I tried to follow the same pattern.

**NOTE,** when `index_t` is defined as `int64_t` I also see 5-10% run time degradation, when 
`int64_t *` memory is used for indexes storage. Therefore, with regard to runtime, this is not the best solution, but at least there is some logic here. Best solution would be use `int64_t` pointers **if and only if** it is impossible to store indexes in `uint32_t` format, otherwise use 
`uint32_t` or `uint_16_t` formats.

Definitely, I could forget about optimization of run time and use **only** the pointers of type `index_t *`. In that case the loop will be quite simple:
```
  while (nWorkers > 1) {
    const size_t num_items = nWorkers * shape.Size() / shape[axis];
    pIdxMemory = AllocateDTypeMemory<xpu, index_t>(ctx, num_items);
    if (pIdxMemory)
       break;
    nWorkers >>= 1;
  }
```

So it looks like we have following three options:
(1) keep current implementation (which looks logical, but note the best one when `index_t` is defined as `int64_t`)
(2) store indexes only `index_t` format (which is the simplest, but not the best one with respect to run time)
(3) implement the **"best"** solution: use `int64_t ` format only when `index_t` is defined as 'int64_t' AND `shape[axis] > UINT32_MAX`  

Which one do you prefer?

