I was originally planning to emit the `<Method>Args` and `<Method>Result` classes as nested classes within the resource's class, e.g.:

```csharp
public class MyResource : ComponentResource
{
    public Output<FooResult> Foo(FooArgs args)
        => ...

    public sealed class FooArgs : Pulumi.CallArgs
    {
        ...
    }

    public sealed class FooResult
    {
    }
}
```

Which is similar to what we've done for Node.js and Python, and appropriately "namespaces" the types to avoid any naming conflicts for similarly named methods on different resources within the same Pulumi module.

However, using these as nested classes from .NET is more annoying which isn't an issue in practice with TS/JS and Python. In .NET you have to do:

```
var res = new MyResource(...);
var result = res.Foo(MyResource.FooArgs(...)); // Kinda annoying
```

When it'd be much nicer to use as:

```
var res = new MyResource(...);
var result = res.Foo(FooArgs(...)); // Nicer
```

This PR currently does the latter nicer approach (non-nested).

**What do folks think?** 

There is some risk that within a Pulumi module, there could be resources that have methods with the same name which then would result in conflicts. If that becomes a problem, we'd have to come up with a way to address it, either by nesting the classes, prefixing the resource name (e.g. `<Resource><Method>Args`), or providing a way to customize the naming from the schema. However, I wonder how common such conflicts would be in practice (same method name on multiple resources in the same module).

Note that in Go, we currently emit these prefixed as `<Resource><Method>Args` and `<Resource><Method>Result`, to prevent such conflicts, but this is also annoying to use, so if we proceed with the unnested, un-resource-prefixed names in C#, I'll open a PR to remove the `<Resource>` prefix from the Go codegen.

